Evaluation
Judging Panel
All submissions will be evaluated by a panel of at least three judges with combined expertise in emergency medicine, clinical AI, and data science. Judges are designated by the Laitinen-Fredriksson Foundation.

Submission Requirements
The following are required for a submission to be considered eligible. Submissions missing any required element will not be scored.

Requirement	Details
Kaggle Notebook	Must run end-to-end without errors. Must be set to public before the submission deadline.
Project Writeup	Submitted via the Kaggle Writeup tab. Must include all sections of the Writeup Template.
Clinical Problem Statement	The writeup must clearly define the specific triage problem being addressed.
Data Disclosure	All datasets used (public or provided) must be cited and described in the notebook.
Scoring Rubric (100 points total)
1. Clinical Relevance (25 points)
Does the submission address a real and meaningful problem in emergency triage? Is the problem statement grounded in clinical reality? Would a practicing emergency physician find this work credible and useful?

Score	Description
21-25	Problem is sharply defined, clinically motivated, and directly relevant to triage workflows. The clinical context is explained with accuracy and depth.
14-20	Problem is relevant but motivation is partially developed or clinical grounding is surface-level.
7-13	Problem relates broadly to emergency medicine but triage relevance is unclear or weakly argued.
0-6	Problem has negligible clinical relevance or clinical context is absent.
2. Technical Quality (30 points)
Is the AI or analytical approach sound? Is the methodology appropriate for the problem? Is the code clean, reproducible, and well-structured?

Score	Description
25-30	Methodology is rigorous and appropriate. Code is reproducible, clean, and well-commented. Modeling choices are justified. Evaluation is thorough and honest about limitations.
17-24	Methodology is reasonable with minor gaps. Code runs correctly. Some justification for choices is provided.
9-16	Methodology has notable weaknesses or the notebook has errors. Limited justification provided.
0-8	Methodology is flawed, code does not run, or approach is not appropriate for the problem.
3. Documentation and Writeup Quality (20 points)
Is the writeup clear, complete, and well-structured? Could a clinician or data scientist reproduce or build on this work from the writeup alone?

Score	Description
17-20	Writeup is thorough, clearly written, and follows the template. Methodology, findings, and limitations are all addressed. Reproducibility is fully supported.
11-16	Writeup covers most required sections with adequate clarity. Some gaps in explanation or structure.
5-10	Writeup is incomplete, unclear, or missing key sections.
0-4	Writeup is absent or provides insufficient information to evaluate the work.
4. Insight and Findings (15 points)
Does the submission produce meaningful, interpretable findings? Are results communicated honestly, including failure modes and uncertainties?

Score	Description
13-15	Findings are meaningful, clearly communicated, and appropriately caveated. Results are interpreted in clinical context.
8-12	Findings are reported but interpretation is limited or not connected to clinical implications.
3-7	Findings are superficial or results are overclaimed without appropriate uncertainty.
0-2	No meaningful findings are presented.
5. Novelty and Impact Potential (10 points)
Does the submission bring a fresh perspective, an underexplored dataset, or an innovative framing of the problem? Could this work plausibly inform real clinical or research practice?

Score	Description
9-10	Approach is genuinely novel or tackles a meaningfully underexplored aspect of triage AI. Impact pathway is clearly articulated.
6-8	Some novel elements present. Impact is plausible but not deeply argued.
3-5	Largely follows established approaches with limited differentiation.
0-2	No novelty evident. Impact pathway is absent or implausible.
Scoring Summary
Criterion	Points
Clinical Relevance	25
Technical Quality	30
Documentation and Writeup Quality	20
Insight and Findings	15
Novelty and Impact Potential	10
Total	100
Judging Process
Evaluation will proceed in three rounds:

Round 1 - Eligibility screening (1-2 judges): All submissions are reviewed against the required elements checklist. Ineligible submissions are removed from consideration.

Round 2 - Detailed scoring (full panel): Each eligible submission is independently scored by at least two judges using the rubric above. Scores are normalized across judges to reduce variance.

Round 3 - Final deliberation (full panel): The top submissions are reviewed collectively. Final rankings are determined by consensus discussion.

The Laitinen-Fredriksson Foundation reserves the right to withhold prizes if an insufficient number of submissions meet the minimum quality threshold.

